WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.600
Hi, my name is Michael Thomas, and I'm the Chief Data Scientist at Ketchbook Analytics.

00:00:10.600 --> 00:00:15.360
I am so excited to be teaching a workshop at this year's PositConf with my great friend

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:20.760
Eric Nance on tools and tips for building a shiny app that can thrive in a production

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:21.760
environment.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:25.840
And I wanted to talk to you about three things that I am so excited about for this workshop.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:29.080
The first is the concept of modularization.

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:34.360
So if you've built a shiny app in the past using a single app.r script, or maybe separate

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:41.400
UI and server scripts, you know that those scripts can get very big very fast.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:45.000
Everything that we will do in this workshop will use shiny modules and will be a great

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:51.279
showcase on how to modularize your code in a way that is much more concise, legible,

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:52.279
and maintainable.

00:00:52.279 --> 00:00:56.439
We'll also show you how to get these modules to talk to each other so that you can begin

00:00:56.439 --> 00:01:01.360
to build shiny apps that are truly ready for a production environment.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:05.959
The second topic that I am so excited about for this workshop is deployment.

00:01:05.959 --> 00:01:10.279
And we know that we can build a great app that works phenomenally well on our own machine.

00:01:10.279 --> 00:01:15.360
But what good is that if we can't share it with end users or a wider audience?

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:19.919
There are a lot of different deployment strategies and techniques, depending on the type of app

00:01:19.919 --> 00:01:24.199
that you are building, who you need to share it with and where you need to share it.

00:01:24.199 --> 00:01:28.480
And this can come down to whether the app is going to be public-facing or private-facing

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:29.480
as well.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:33.639
And this is one of the trickiest parts of the whole shiny app development process and

00:01:33.639 --> 00:01:36.879
perhaps one of the parts that gets talked about the least.

00:01:36.879 --> 00:01:41.879
So we are thrilled to be able to make this a part of our workshop and walk you through

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:45.959
these different deployment strategies so that you can come out of this workshop with a great

00:01:45.959 --> 00:01:51.080
understanding of how you will deploy apps within your own organization or for your own

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:52.800
use case.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:58.320
And the last thing that I am so excited about in this workshop is the fact that user experience

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:01.959
will be a theme around everything that we do in the workshop.

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:05.239
The concept of defending your UI will get talked about.

00:02:05.239 --> 00:02:10.800
How easy is it for users to take an action within your app that they can't undo?

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:14.960
How performant is your app when multiple users are using it concurrently?

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:20.279
We are going to put ourselves in the shoes of the server side of our app and think about

00:02:20.279 --> 00:02:26.399
how often it's listening or how often it needs to be listening to users and actions.

00:02:26.399 --> 00:02:31.500
After all, our shiny app could be housing a complex machine learning model or running

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:33.759
an intensive Bayesian simulation.

00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:38.880
But depending on how easy it is for users to navigate, the app can mean the difference

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:44.860
between massive adoption of your app within the organization or nobody really using it

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:47.460
and all of that hard work going to waste.

00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:51.660
So we sincerely hope that you join us for this workshop and we are so excited to see

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:52.660
you in Chicago.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:58.940
Hello, I'm Eric Nanz and I'm so excited to be teaching a workshop at this year's PositConf

00:02:58.940 --> 00:03:04.380
all about tools and techniques to help you run your shiny application successfully in

00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:05.380
production.

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:10.300
And here are the top three reasons why I think you might benefit from this workshop.

00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:15.259
Across the community, you will find terrific resources centered around effective shiny development

00:03:15.259 --> 00:03:16.259
best practices.

00:03:17.059 --> 00:03:22.820
After you deploy your application, you might encounter issues that you did not have happen

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:28.460
when it was just you developing the application and you might find yourself asking, hey, it

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:30.580
worked just fine on my machine.

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:34.779
In this workshop, we're going to tell you about effective principles that can help you

00:03:34.779 --> 00:03:42.220
plan for the unexpected, such as effective profiling of your application's resource usage,

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:48.100
the ways that you can simultaneously simulate hundreds or even thousands of users accessing

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:54.100
your application at once, and effective testing strategies from both the backend and user

00:03:54.100 --> 00:04:01.059
interface perspectives to help illuminate issues before your users encounter them.

00:04:01.059 --> 00:04:07.139
As your shiny application grows in complexity, you may find it handling many different tasks

00:04:07.139 --> 00:04:11.380
all at once, which can lead to degraded performance.

00:04:11.539 --> 00:04:15.660
So in this workshop, we're going to teach you ways that you can make your application

00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:22.000
actually do less, only do what it needs to do, such as tapping into external resources

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:29.220
for data sources or leveraging APIs to help with some additional processing and ways that

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:35.500
you can organize the way objects are stored in your application, which may greatly streamline

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:41.019
the processing and give your users that snappy feeling that you want them to have when they

00:04:41.019 --> 00:04:42.019
visit your app.

00:04:42.019 --> 00:04:47.100
Well, in this workshop, much like the rest of the material, we're going to go hands-on

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:52.359
and explore these different deploying strategies together and look at the different advantages

00:04:52.359 --> 00:04:57.100
and perhaps even pitfalls that you might encounter throughout these options.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:01.779
And you're going to get hands-on experience with platforms such as Posit Connect, and

00:05:01.779 --> 00:05:07.059
we'll also explore container technology for even more flexible options available to you

00:05:07.059 --> 00:05:08.619
for deployment.

00:05:08.619 --> 00:05:14.859
I'm really passionate about enabling shiny users that take their skills to the next level,

00:05:14.859 --> 00:05:20.859
especially in this very important area of successfully running your application in production.

00:05:20.859 --> 00:05:25.739
I hope you join me at this year's PositConf for this exciting workshop.

00:05:25.739 --> 00:05:31.059
And to register, just visit posit.co slash conference for all the details.

00:05:31.059 --> 00:05:32.339
I hope to see you there.

